data.content:
Yes — MSTest 3.7+ supports **ValueTuple** return types with `DynamicData`, eliminating the `object[]` casts:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- Return type: `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)>`
- Data entries: `["value", true]` → `("value", true)`

The test method signature stays the same — MSTest destructures the tuple into the parameters automatically. You get compile-time type checking on your test data, so mismatched types are caught before the test even runs.

Requires **MSTest 3.7+** (the `MSTest` metapackage or `MSTest.Sdk`).
